      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon in quantum physics where two or more particles become interconnected and instantaneously affect each other's states, irrespective of the distance between them. This interconnectedness means the measurement outcome of one particle's state immediately affects the related state of its entangled partner(s). Unlike classical correlation, where entangled particles are not affected by measurements remotely, regeneration of classical systems also doesn't follow this instant effect, defying classical physics laws. Entanglement forms the bedrock of quantum mechanics and has significant implications in quantum computing and teleportation.",
