    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks that makes sense. i keep seeing people call it \"spooky action at a distance\" though. why is that specific term used? it sounds a bit weird for a science topic lol",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Alain Aspect, one of the physicists who contributed significantly to understanding quantum entanglement, initially coined the phrase \"spooky action at a distance\" to illustrate how the properties of entangled particles seemed to behave at a distance as if they were communicating instantaneously, which seemed hard to digest given our classical understanding. Einstein referred to this entanglement he found troubling in his theory of relativity as a form of \"spooky action.\" It's \"spooky,\" not because it's an esoteric concept, but rather because it challenges our conventional understanding of cause and effect, making it seem like nearer particles influence one another instantly. Even in the scientific community, it remained a concept that puzzled and fascinated. Now it's understood as a real phenomenon explained by quantum mechanics, despite the absence of any traditional signal transmission.",
      "source": "target",
